This definition seems to get confused with universe variables if I actually try to use it.

Without the `{0}` this gives
```
type mismatch
  Fin Â«$nÂ»
has type
  Type : Type 1
but is expected to have type
  Type 127 : Type 128
  ```

Yes, this is the `ToLevel` issue I've alluded to on Zulip.  Depending on the order the instances are synthesized, we can end up searching for an instance of `ToLevel.{?u}`.  And since the succ instances has higher priority than the zero instance, we get `ToLevel.{127}` as a result.  If we'd swap the instance priorities, we'd get `ToLevel.{0}`.  Of course, neither choice is desirable.
What's the motivation for giving this a standalone def? Can't we just use the typeclass-parametrized `toExprQ`?

It would be possible to inline the definition here into the instance (and that's in fact how you should call it).  I usually try to make separate definitions for the operations to reduce the size of the instance after unfolding.  Whenever Lean reduces, for example, `ToExprQ.level`, it needs to copy the whole instance body, including both the `toTypeExprQ` definition and the even larger (when inlined) `toExprQ` definition.

(For other type classes like `Ring` there's an additional benefit:  When we check that two instances of, for example, `Add` are defeq, it is obviously much faster to check that `Fin.add =?= Fin.add` than to compare the definitions, which have modulo operators, additional type class arguments, etc.)

Writing proofs inside the instance is completely fine though, because Lean will automatically create auxiliary `_proof_7` lemmas for you.
